    "The next results formalize both constructions:Proposition 1 When R is a standard topology on X Â E, s R ¼ n ðÇ A; EÞ j A 2 R o is a soft topology on X.If s 0 is a soft topology on X, then Rðs 0 Þ ¼ n A ðG; EÞ j ðG; EÞ 2 s 0 o is a standard topology on X Â E.We are ready to state the fundamental theorem of soft topology:Theorem 1 ([48, 174, 176]) T: f Topological spaces on X Â Eg À!ST E ðXÞ ðX Â E; RÞ s Rdefines a bijective function with inverse functionT À1: ST E ðXÞ À!f Topological spaces on X Â Eg s ðX Â E; RðsÞÞSince [174] it is known that with this theorem one can transform results from general topology to soft topology (see also [48,60,175] for more arguments supporting this claim)."
